Steepest local search with edge exchange and cost delta optimization¶

def local_search(tsp, solution):
    if solution is None:
        solution = random_solution(tsp)

    while True:
        delta_inter, *move_inter = find_best_inter(tsp, solution)
        delta_intra, *move_intra = find_best_intra(tsp, solution)

        if delta_inter < delta_intra:
            delta = delta_inter
            move = move_inter
        else:
            delta = delta_intra
            move = move_intra

        if delta < 0:
            apply_move(solution, *move)
        else:
            return solution

def find_best_inter(tsp, solution):
    node_a is one of the nodes in the solution
    node_b is one of the nodes not in the solution

    result = [0, "inter", None, None]

    for each combination of node_a and node_b:
        node_prev = solution[index_a - 1]
        node_next = solution[index_a + 1]

        delta = (
                tsp.node_costs[node_b]
                + tsp.distance_matrix[node_prev, node_b]
                + tsp.distance_matrix[node_b, node_next]
                - tsp.node_costs[node_a]
                - tsp.distance_matrix[node_prev, node_a]
                - tsp.distance_matrix[node_a, node_next]
            )

        if delta < result[0]:
            result = [delta, "inter", node_a, node_b]

    return result


def find_best_intra(tsp, solution):
    node_a and node_b are distinct nodes in the solution
    node_a is precedent to node_b

    result = [0, "intra", None, None]

    for each combination of node_a and node_b:
        node_a_next = solution[index_a + 1]
        node_b_next = solution[index_b + 1]

        delta = (
            tsp.distance_matrix[node_a, node_b]
            + tsp.distance_matrix[node_a_next, node_b_next]
            - tsp.distance_matrix[node_a, node_a_next]
            - tsp.distance_matrix[node_b, node_b_next]
        )

        if delta < result[0]:
            result = [delta, "intra", node_a, node_b]

    return result

def apply_move(solution move_type, node_a, node_b):
    if move_type == "inter":
        solution[index_a] = node_b
    else:
        solution[index_a+1:index_b+1] = solution[index_a+1:index_b+1][::-1]

Time Limit¶

One run of our local search implementation takes from 8 to 12 seconds.

In order to complete the calculations in reasonable time a limit of 1 minute per iteration is imposed on both MLSL and ILS (while still allowing the current iteration of local search to finish).

That means that:

  1. MLSL will choose the best of approximately 6 local search solutions
  2. ILS will generate a random solution and will improve it by perturbation and local search for approximately 6 times

Multiple start local search¶

def msls(tsp):
    best_solution = None
    while execution time < 1 minute:
        solution = local_search(tsp)
        if tsp.get_cost(solution) < tsp.get_cost(best_solution) or best_solution is None:
            best_solution = solution
    return solution

Iterated local search¶

def ils(tsp):
    best_solution = local_search(tsp) # start with local search from a random solution
    while execution time < 1 minute:
        solution = local_search(tsp, perturb(best_solution)) # perturb the best solution and repeat local search
        if tsp.get_cost(solution) < tsp.get_cost(best_solution) or best_solution is None:
            best_solution = solution
    return solution

Perturbation:

  1. Copy the solution
  2. For 10 times: select a node in the solution and replace it with a random node in or out of the solution
    • if both nodes are in the solution than swap them
    • if the second node is out of the solution than replace the first node with the second node
  3. For 3 times: randomly select a segment of the solution of up to 5 nodes and shuffle it
    start = np.random.randint(len(solution))
 np.random.shuffle(solution[start:start+5])

The implemented perturbation allows to change up to 25% of the solution, which proves to be the optimal amount.

Results¶

Both MSLS and ILS were run for 20 times each. The total execution time per algorithm is around 20 minutes.

Conclusions¶

  • ILS gives better results than MSLS on both problem instances
  • There is virtually no difference in performance (speed) between ILS and MSLS
  • Worsening results in comparison to previous methods can be explained by two factors:
    • New experiments were run on a slower computer that the previous one
    • New experiments were limited in time to 1 minute per iteration and 20 minutes per experiment, while the previous experiments were not limited
